vdma: hold mmap_read_lock around find_vma() in hailo_vdma_buffer_map

On Linux 6.12+, find_vma() asserts that the caller holds the mmap read
lock (mmap_assert_locked() in include/linux/rwsem.h). The 4.21.0 Hailo
PCIe driver calls find_vma(current->mm, addr_or_fd) without that lock in
hailo_vdma_buffer_map(), so every DMA buffer map ioctl trips a WARN:

    WARNING: CPU: .. at include/linux/rwsem.h:80 find_vma+0x59/0x70
     hailo_vdma_buffer_map+0x103/0x7e0 [hailo_pci]
     hailo_vdma_buffer_map_ioctl+0xbb/0x280 [hailo_pci]
     hailo_pcie_fops_unlockedioctl+0x1bd/0x6d0 [hailo_pci]

It is usually "just" a WARN, but has been reported to escalate to an oops
during active inference (Errno 5 I/O on the recordings volume).

This is Hailo's own fix, taken verbatim from upstream hailort-drivers
commit 8edb23b ("Suggested-by: Paul Kocialkowski"), which shipped in
v4.22.0. Upstream then *reverted* it in v4.23.0 (the two lock lines were
deleted again), so neither the version we pin (4.21.0, to match Frigate's
bundled libhailort) nor the current hailo8-branch tip carries it. We
re-apply it at build time.

Note: this matches upstream's narrow critical section — the lock is
dropped immediately after find_vma() even though `vma` is dereferenced
afterwards (is_dmabuf_vma/create_fd_from_vma/vma->vm_flags). That is
enough to satisfy mmap_assert_locked() and stop the WARN/oops, and keeps
us byte-identical to what Hailo shipped in 4.22.0. Do not widen the scope
without re-checking against upstream.

diff --git a/linux/vdma/memory.c b/linux/vdma/memory.c
index 7ad4a68..7a78cc5 100644
--- a/linux/vdma/memory.c
+++ b/linux/vdma/memory.c
@@ -167,7 +167,9 @@ struct hailo_vdma_buffer *hailo_vdma_buffer_map(struct device *dev,
     }

     if (HAILO_DMA_DMABUF_BUFFER != buffer_type) {
+        mmap_read_lock(current->mm);
         vma = find_vma(current->mm, addr_or_fd);
+        mmap_read_unlock(current->mm);
         if (IS_ENABLED(HAILO_SUPPORT_MMIO_DMA_MAPPING)) {
             if (NULL == vma) {
                 dev_err(dev, "no vma for virt_addr/size = 0x%08lx/0x%08zx\n", addr_or_fd, size);
